 Deutschland":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Duitsland","Of, AUGSBURG,SCHWABEN,BAYERN":"Landkreis Augsburg, Bayern, Duitsland","Germany":"Duitsland"},"en":{"1268–06 JUL 1325":"1268–6 July 1325","1267–Female":"1267–Deceased","1268–1325":"1268–1325","1275–1330":"1275–1330","1293–Female":"1293–Deceased","1294–1370":"1294–1370","1324–Female":"1324–Deceased","1220–1273":"1220–1273","1235–Female":"1235–Deceased","about 1260":"about 1260","about 1294":"about 1294","after 1293":"1293","1220":"1220","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","Abt 1324":"about 1324","1273":"1273","1294":"1294","1293":"1293","1370":"1370","nach 1273":"after 1273","1325":"1325","1324":"1324","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","06 JUL 1325":"6 July 1325","Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","Augsburg, , , Bayern, Deutschland":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","Of, AUGSBURG,SCHWABEN,BAYERN":"Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany","Germany":"Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"REHM","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernd, Otto, Armin, Hans, Gunter, Hermann, Lothar, Oskar.","German: from the medieval personal name <i>Rehm</i> (see   Remy  ).","German: from Middle High German <i>reme</i> ‘frame, loom, rack’, hence a metonymic occupational name for someone who made or used such items."],"variants":[{"name":"Rahm","meanings":["German:","topographic name from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>rām(e)</i> ‘end, target, mark’, or a habitational name from any of several places in Westphalia and Rhineland named with this word. This surname (in any of the possible senses; see also below) is also found in France (Alsace).","from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>rām</i> ‘soot’, possibly a metonymic occupational name for a blacksmith or charcoal burner, or a nickname for a dirty person."]},{"name":"Rohm","meanings":["German:","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ruom</i> (Old High German <i>hruom</i> ‘fame’), a short form of <i>Ruombald</i> and similar personal names containing this element.","(<b>Röhm</b>): variant of   Rehm  . Compare   Roehm  ."]},{"name":"Rhem","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Rehm   or its variant <b>Remm</b>. This surname is found mainly among African Americans.","History: The progenitor of many of the Rhems was Melcher Rhem (or, as spelled in the surviving documents, <i>Remm</i>) from Germany, who died in 1768 in Craven County, NC. He had three sons, all surnamed <i>Rhem</i>."]},{"name":"Remy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Andre, Jean-Claude, Evens, Germaine, Gisele, Henri, Hugues, Jacques, Jean Raymond, Jean-Daniel, Josee, Laurent.","French (<b>Rémy</b>); West Indian (in Haiti, Martinique, and Guadeloupe <b>Rémy</b>); Walloon and German: from a French personal name which represents a falling together of two distinct Latin names: <i>Remigius</i> (a derivative of <i>remex</i>, genitive <i>remigis</i> ‘rower, oarsman’), and <i>Remedius</i> (from <i>remedium</i> ‘cure, remedy’). The former name was borne by a 6th-century bishop of Rheims; the latter was borne by various other Christian saints of the 8th to 10th centuries. Compare   Ramey  ,   Reamy  , and   Rhamy  .","History: The surname <i>Rémy</i> of French origin is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors, once along with its altered forms <i>Ramey</i> and <i>Remey</i>, and once along with the variant <i>de Rémi</i> and altered forms <i>Reamy</i> and <i>Remey</i>. It is also listed in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America. One of Huguenot ancestors was Jacques Rémy, born <i>c.</i> 1630 in France, who by 1672 lived in Westmoreland County, VA, where he died in 1721. Many of his descendants bear the surname   Ramey  , some also   Rhamy  . — Léopold Rémy <i>dit</i> Bellefleur from Biécourt in the Vosges married Marie-Angélique Trudel in L'Ange-Gardien, QC, in 1758."]},{"name":"Roehm","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Klaus, Eberhard, Gerhard.","German (<b>Röhm</b>): variant of   Rehm  . Compare   Rohm   2."]},{"name":"Rem","meanings":["German: perhaps an altered form of   Rehm  .","American shortened form of Polish <b>Rembowski</b>: unexplained.","Dutch: from the personal name <i>Rem</i>, a short form of   Remmert   or   Rembert  ."]},{"name":"Rehmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","North German: topographic name for someone who lived in a marshy place, from Middle Low German <i>red</i> ‘bog’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’.","North German: variant of   Rehm   2, with the addition of Middle Low German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]}]},{"name":"Berthold","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["<i>berht</i> ‘bright’ + <i>hold</i> ‘splendid’; alteration of earlier <i>Bertwald</i>, from <i>berht</i> + <i>wald</i> ‘rule, power’."],"variants":[{"name":"Barthold","meanings":["form of   Berthold ."]}]},{"name":"Der","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]},{"name":"Ältere","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably an altered form of German   Alter   or of Dutch, German, or possibly English   Alders  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Alter","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Berthold Der Ältere REHM was born in 1268, in Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany, his father, Heinrich II Rehm, was 48 and his mother, Katharina Portner von Wellenburg, was 33. He married Hiltgard Ilsung in 1293, in Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died on 6 July 1325, in his hometown, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1268–06 JUL 1325":"1268–6. juuli 1325","1267–Female":"1267–Surnud","1268–1325":"1268–1325","1275–1330":"1275–1330","1293–Female":"1293–Surnud","1294–1370":"1294–1370","1324–Female":"1324–Surnud","1220–1273":"1220–1273","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","about 1294":"umbes 1294","after 1293":"1293","1220":"1220","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","Abt 1324":"umbes 1324","1273":"1273","1294":"1294","1293":"1293","1370":"1370","nach 1273":"pärast 1273","1325":"1325","1324":"1324","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","06 JUL 1325":"6. juuli 1325","Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Saksamaa","Augsburg, , , Bayern, Deutschland":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Saksamaa","Of, AUGSBURG,SCHWABEN,BAYERN":"Landkreis Augsburg, Bayern, Saksamaa","Germany":"Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1268–06 JUL 1325":"1268–6. heinäkuuta 1325","1267–Female":"1267–Kuollut","1268–1325":"1268–1325","1275–1330":"1275–1330","1293–Female":"1293–Kuollut","1294–1370":"1294–1370","1324–Female":"1324–Kuollut","1220–1273":"1220–1273","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","about 1260":"noin 1260","about 1294":"noin 1294","after 1293":"1293","1220":"1220","1330":